WEBVTT

00:02.427 --> 00:03.649
We're going to beat that rascal this year. We know 
that a number of the students who were in schools at

00:05.551 --> 00:13.682
the time you were there had various and sundry 
jobs. Were you ever employed while you were a

00:14.784 --> 00:17.647
student? Oh, for three months I calibrated 
electric meters there in the electrical

00:18.028 --> 00:23.495
engineering department. That was all. But quite a 
few of the boys did have that kind of thing. Can you

00:29.103 --> 00:31.506
recall some of the kinds of things that they did? 
old janitor work and that kind of thing and over in

00:32.347 --> 00:53.918
the creamery and probably in the dairy barn and and

00:32.347 --> 00:53.918
oh I don't know it seemed like it might have been a 
minority of those boys and they were probably busy

00:32.347 --> 00:53.918
at the job and off somewhere and you just didn't 
notice it too much. I was wondering did any of them

00:53.978 --> 00:56.301
ever work for any of the professors? You mean in the 
professor's home? Yeah, or do things around. Of

01:04.003 --> 01:07.106
course, I guess the college maintained the houses 
since they owned them. Oh, yes. Well, not in the

01:09.248 --> 01:11.150
professor's homes. They might have, but I don't 
know anything about it.

01:16.336 --> 01:19.519
At that point, I guess there wasn't a whole lot of 
babysitting to do. At a later period, I think some

01:19.879 --> 01:22.963
of them did babysitting for the faculty. Well, in 
that day and time, I don't think there's much

01:22.983 --> 01:29.910
babysitting going on because I didn't know about 
it. Did the students who played on the college

01:31.527 --> 01:43.262
football and baseball and basketball teams and so 
forth have privileges that the other students

01:31.527 --> 01:43.262
didn't have? Oh, yes. They had what they called, 
one thing was the mess hall. They called it the

01:46.706 --> 01:47.908
training table. And of course, they got special 
stakes and those kind of things, and that kind of

01:47.928 --> 01:53.755
thing. I don't believe they had to attend Reveille 
in the morning. You know, they had Reveille every

01:56.466 --> 01:58.715
morning, get out and exercise. I don't believe 
they had to go through that. And they were, a lot of

02:01.125 --> 02:04.639
times they were excused from the evening 
formation, you know, because they didn't get back

02:05.243 --> 02:10.074
in time in that kind of time. They were excused from 
quite a few things like that. They almost had to be

02:13.080 --> 02:14.984
in order to participate. What about, were they, 
were the officers as strict on them as far as their

02:15.826 --> 02:23.944
uniform inspection and so forth is concerned? Oh, 
yes, I think so. I was in the Signal Corps the last

02:25.393 --> 02:32.145
year I was there, and Ruby Drake was one of the 
greatest tackles we ever had down there. Well, he

02:32.205 --> 02:36.632
dressed just like the rest of us, and they 
inspected him just like they did the rest of us. I

02:36.652 --> 02:42.422
know about him because he was, you know, some of 
them, they might have been a little more lax on, but

02:36.652 --> 02:42.422
not Ruby Drake. Okay, during the, I guess this 
would have been what, during your junior year was

02:44.883 --> 02:56.595
when they had the most active participation in the 
First World War. What changes did this bring about

02:57.776 --> 03:04.023
as far as your experiences were concerned? Well, 
it brought about quite a few changes because it

03:05.124 --> 03:13.573
went back down in the

03:05.124 --> 03:13.573
fall of 1918. registered for school. That was when 
the World War was on then. And, you know, all the

03:18.651 --> 03:30.257
upperclassmen had gone to these training camps, 
these juniors and seniors, and that left just

03:18.651 --> 03:30.257
about all that was there was the freshmen and we 
sophomores. And Of course, they had these young

03:33.314 --> 03:39.445
lieutenants come in there to train us, that kind of 
thing, and some of them was only two, three years

03:33.314 --> 03:39.445
older than we were, you know. And it was different 
in a way. We tried to maintain all the customs and

03:43.272 --> 03:51.047
those kind of things, but it was a noticeable 
difference, I think, during that period. But it

03:51.428 --> 03:53.331
didn't last long, thank goodness. I believe it 
only lasted from like September of 1918 to what,

03:53.817 --> 03:59.522
the beginning of the next term. Yes, that's right, 
the next term. You know, we were all enlisted in the

04:01.304 --> 04:17.818
Army there, sworn in, probably about the first of 
October 1918, and then they discharged shortly

04:01.304 --> 04:17.818
after the Armistice, probably early December. I 
don't remember the exact date. Were you enlisted

04:19.399 --> 04:21.941
in what was called the SATC? SATC, Student Army 
Training Corps, yes, sir. And you still attended

04:24.530 --> 04:26.853
GLSIS, I take it? Oh yes, we did, and that's right, 
and we specialized on military, you know, and

04:26.873 --> 04:40.508
these officers would talk to us and train us, and 
they'd begin to sort us out to go to future training

04:26.873 --> 04:40.508
camps in case the war continued. I was slated to go 
to an artillery camp, but you know, the war ended

04:41.409 --> 04:45.633
before I reached that point. And I think the, 
particularly the seniors who came back were,

04:50.399 --> 04:54.263
enrolled in in January, and they did kind of a hurry 
up two semesters. Hurry up a semester. I think they

04:56.285 --> 04:58.067
ran over in June sometime. But it hurried up to get 
them through there and to graduate them. And so

05:01.972 --> 05:10.501
actually, you didn't really have any 
participation in the war effort other than being

05:01.972 --> 05:10.501
in the SATC for a couple months. That's right, on 
the campus, a couple months. Let's

05:14.225 --> 05:19.090
see.

05:25.229 --> 05:33.198
I noticed here from your senior yearbook, you were 
in G Company, what, the first regiment? Yes, sir.

05:35.000 --> 05:35.781
For three years? Yes, sir. And let's see. Company 
of Signal Corps after that. Okay. I have you being

05:40.967 --> 05:50.498
as a fish in Company G1 and a sophomore in Company 
G1, and then you were in a sergeant in G Company, and

05:40.967 --> 05:50.498
then you went to first sergeant in A Company Signal 
Corps. Right, right. When was that, when did you

05:52.162 --> 05:54.486
switch to the signal corps? Was that... That was 
January 1919 when the seniors came back. I was a

06:00.376 --> 06:02.419
first sergeant. That period from January to June. 
So it was kind of, so did all the students then go

06:05.224 --> 06:10.132
through June instead of not just the seniors? The 
whole college. The whole college went until June.

06:13.846 --> 06:17.412
And then a lot of us went to camp, military camp. I 
went back with a group back to Louisville,

06:17.492 --> 06:22.420
Kentucky to an infantry camp after the war, right 
after June. Right after June until then you came

06:22.501 --> 06:28.791
back in September again for the senior year, and 
then you were captain in the Signal Corps then.

06:28.811 --> 06:29.312
Company A. So that's when you got your free pass to 
the theater. Oh, yes. You were also, I take it, in

06:36.364 --> 06:38.948
the RVs. Yeah, I was in the RV, yes, sir. Fine 
organization. What? Fine organization. What was

06:44.742 --> 06:48.666
the procedure for becoming a member of the RVs? 
Well, it was a secret ballot. Of course, I didn't

06:51.249 --> 06:54.192
know my name written proposed. I don't know who 
proposed it. These RVs, they met and then they

06:55.973 --> 07:05.723
announced who they had elected to join the 
organization. And that was in the afternoon, they

07:06.091 --> 07:07.893
announced it. And of course, the RVs then went over 
cases, which was a confectionery in that Y, in

07:08.594 --> 07:18.304
order to box cigars or peas or drinks and charge it 
to the new RVs. And of course, we had to divide up and

07:18.364 --> 07:20.326
pay the bill. So I knew nothing about it until I was 
notified I'd been elected. A happy occasion. What

07:29.555 --> 07:32.318
sort of things did the RVs do? Well, of course, they 
had a dance every year. They called it the RV dance.

07:39.255 --> 07:43.441
And then we had special drills, military drills, 
precision drills. And then at the end of the year,

07:43.461 --> 07:50.250
we'd compete on these drills, who would be the best 
drill man, and that kind of thing. That was within

07:50.590 --> 07:51.632
the RVs? Yes, RVs. So you had kind of a double amount 
of drilling to do then, as you remember. Were you in

07:57.980 --> 08:00.944
the RVs as both a junior and a senior? No. No, my 
senior year, my senior year. But I believe both

08:05.762 --> 08:07.747
juniors and seniors were eligible. Yes, they 
were, but mine, junior year, I mean senior year.

08:11.395 --> 08:14.261
Was that generally the case, most of them were 
seniors? Well, I'd say... I'd say the majority of

08:18.586 --> 08:20.469
them were yes. Yes, I think so. Although, you know, 
they had a nucleus to come on next year to carry the

08:22.031 --> 08:26.598
organization on. I think there's more than 50% of 
them seniors, yes, as I recall. So then you had a

08:30.564 --> 08:35.391
special uniform which you wore just 
occasionally. Yes, that's right. He has a white

08:37.394 --> 08:41.119
uniform and gold braid and all that kind of stuff. 
You wore this to the RV hop and other occasions.

08:43.423 --> 08:46.467
Yeah, the RV hop, yeah, that's right, and the 
drills and... special occasions that we dressed

08:47.543 --> 08:49.947
in the Army uniform.

08:53.412 --> 08:56.156
And I noticed you were also a member of the senior 
court. Yes, I was. In those days, instead of the

08:58.340 --> 09:13.804
military office punishing boys, they decided for 
a while after this senior court made up of seniors

08:58.340 --> 09:13.804
to find out what was going on and the circumstances 
and mete out punishment. to these guilty persons.

09:17.061 --> 09:25.369
And we'd bring the boys in and question them and 
find out both sides, just like a regular court. And

09:25.950 --> 09:28.653
then they'd issue a punishment. And of course, the 
cadet colonel and some of those were on top of it.

09:32.276 --> 09:35.920
And they had a couple of commanders on the thing. 
They tried to get it all over so they'd have

09:35.940 --> 09:38.683
representation. But how many were on the senior 
court? Oh, I'd say Might have been 20, not over 20,

09:43.501 --> 09:47.166
as I recall. This would have been then, say, after 
the World War I, when they did the senior court?

09:51.411 --> 09:51.791
Yes, oh yes. That was my senior year. To my 
knowledge, they didn't have it before then. They

09:54.855 --> 09:55.276
might have. But what sort of infractions would the 
senior court work upon? The violations of

10:02.685 --> 10:04.427
military discipline? Well, yes, and then staying 
over in Brown, maybe without pass, or going

10:04.507 --> 10:12.597
without pass, or... Now I know one case, one of the 
upperclassmen made a very derogatory remark,

10:12.728 --> 10:20.558
there's company command there. Well, they, 
things like that, you know, bring that up and

10:20.578 --> 10:25.524
thrash that out. What did you do then? Did you, you 
would decide upon punishment, would this be

10:26.905 --> 10:31.791
issuing a certain amount of demerits? Demerits, 
that kind of thing, or yes, maybe sometimes they'd

10:31.811 --> 10:40.542
confine them to campus too, you know, and confine 
them to campus, demerits. Were these demerits

10:41.703 --> 10:48.289
then announced at the evening meal as had been the 
custom before? A couple of people I've talked to

10:49.991 --> 10:53.514
said every night at supper they read the RAM list 
for the day. I don't recall that they read the

10:53.534 --> 10:58.418
special. No, I don't recall that. And I don't 
recall the RAM list at mealtime. I don't recall

11:04.524 --> 11:05.925
that. I might do that another period, you know. Not 
in my time. I don't remember. Mm-hmm. I don't think

